For $\Delta t$ small, Taylor expansion of $u(x,t+\Delta t)$ with respect
to time variable about \emph{(x,t)} gives

\begin{align*}
~u(x,t+\Delta t) = u(x,t) + u_{t}(x,t) \Delta t + O((\Delta t)^2)
\end{align*}

This reminds us of the forward difference approximation for the time
derivative:

\begin{align*}
u_{t}(x,t) \approx \frac{u(x,t+\Delta t)-u(x,t)}{\Delta t}
\end{align*}

which has error of $O(\Delta t)$, i.e. first order accurate.

Similarly, for $\Delta x$ small, Taylor expansion of $u(x+\Delta x, t)$
with respect to the space variable about \emph{(x,t)} gives

\begin{align*}
u(x+\Delta x, t) = u(x,t) + u_{x}(x,t) \Delta x + \frac{1}{2!} u_{xx}(x,t) (\Delta x)^2 + \frac{1}{3!} u_{xxx}(x,t) (\Delta x)^2 O((\Delta x)^4)
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
u(x-\Delta x, t) = u(x,t) - u_{x}(x,t) \Delta x + \frac{1}{2!} u_{xx}(x,t) (\Delta x)^2 - \frac{1}{3!} u_{xxx}(x,t) (\Delta x)^3+ O((\Delta x)^4)
\end{align*}

This reminds us of the centered difference approximation for the second
space derivative:

\begin{align*}
u_{xx}(x,t) \approx \frac{u(x+\Delta x,t)-2u(x,t)+u(x-\Delta x,t)}{\Delta x^2}
\end{align*}

which has an error of $O(\Delta x^2)$, i.e. second order accurate.

Putting these back to the equation gives

\begin{align*}
\frac{u(x,t+\Delta t)-u(x,t)}{\Delta t} = \frac{u(x+\Delta x,t)-2u(x,t)+u(x-\Delta x,t)}{\Delta x^2} \quad + \quad t \quad + \quad O(\Delta t, \Delta x^2)
\end{align*}

With uniform time step $~\Delta t = t_{max} / K$ and mesh spacing
$~\Delta x=1/N$, let $~ x_n = n \Delta x$, where $n=0,1,2,...,N$; and
$~ t_k = k \Delta t$, where $k=0,1,2,...,K$; and
$u_{n}^{k} = u(x_n,t_k)$.

Plug these mesh points onto the above gives a linear system with
variables $u_{n}^{k}$. (Note that some of these values are not unknown,
but can be calculated directly using the boundary conditions.)

Work out an equation for a fixed \emph{n} and \emph{k}, showing
$u_n^{k+1}$ in terms of values from the previous time step, i.e.
$u_n^k, u_{n-1}^k, u_{n+1}^k$.

Then consider what should $u_{n}^{k}$ be when $k=0$ and when $n=0,N$

Be reminded that the left Neumann condition

\begin{align*}
~ u_x(0,t) = 0
\end{align*}

is tricky in that you need again to use the centered difference formula
for first derivative to incorporate that. You might want to add a
``fictional'' point to do that.

