By the Taylor series expansion,

\begin{align*}
u(x,t + \Delta t) = u(x,t) + \Delta t \; u_t(x,t) + O((\Delta t)^2)  . \,
\end{align*}
If we isolate $u_t(x,t)$ in the above, we get that

\begin{align*}
u_t(x,t) = \frac{u(x,t+ \Delta t) - u(x,t)}{\Delta t}  .
\end{align*}

Similarly, by Taylor series expansion, we have

\begin{align*}
u(x + \Delta x, t) = u(x,t) + \Delta x \; u_x(x,t) + \frac{(\Delta x)^2}{2!} u_{xx}(x,t) + \frac{(\Delta x)^3}{3!} u_{xxx}(x,t) + O((\Delta x)^4)
\end{align*}
and

\begin{align*}
u(x - \Delta x, t) = u(x,t) - \Delta x \; u_x(x,t) + \frac{(\Delta x)^2}{2!} u_{xx}(x,t) - \frac{(\Delta x)^3}{3!} u_{xxx}(x,t) + O((\Delta x)^4)  .
\end{align*}
If we add the two equations above together, we get that

\begin{align*}
u(x + \Delta x, t) + u(x - \Delta x, t) = 2 u(x,t) + (\Delta x)^2 u_{xx}(x,t) + O((\Delta x)^4)  . \,
\end{align*}
If we isolate $u_{xx}(x,t)$ in the above, we get that

\begin{align*}
u_{xx}(x,t) = \frac{ u(x + \Delta x, t) - 2 u(x,t) + u(x - \Delta x, t)}{(\Delta x)^2} + O((\Delta x)^2) .
\end{align*}

From these, we see that we can approximate $u_t(x,t)$ by

\begin{align*}
u_t(x,t) \approx  \frac{u(x,t+ \Delta t) - u(x,t)}{\Delta t}
\end{align*} and
$u_{xx}(x,t)$ by

\begin{align*}
u_{xx}(x,t) \approx  \frac{ u(x + \Delta x, t) - 2 u(x,t) + u(x - \Delta x, t)}{(\Delta x)^2}  .
\end{align*}

Hence, we can approximate the equation

\begin{align*}
u_t = u_xx + t  \,
\end{align*} by

\begin{align*}
\frac{u(x,t+ \Delta t) - u(x,t)}{\Delta t} = \frac{ u(x + \Delta x, t) - 2 u(x,t) + u(x - \Delta x, t)}{(\Delta x)^2} + t .
\end{align*}
If we isolate $u(x,t+ \Delta t)$ in the above, we get that

\begin{align*}
u(x,t+ \Delta t) = u(x,t) + \frac{\Delta t}{(\Delta x)^2}[u(x + \Delta x, t) - 2 u(x,t) + u(x - \Delta x, t)] + t \Delta t  . \;\;\; \text{(1)}
\end{align*}

Next we will put $N+1$ mesh points in the interval $[0,1]$. Let

\begin{align*}
x_n = n \Delta x \;\; \text{for} \;\; n = 0,1,2, \cdots, N
\end{align*} where

\begin{align*}
\Delta x = \frac{1}{N} .
\end{align*} Here, $x_0 = 0$ and $x_N = 1$. Similarly,
we will let the mesh points in $t$ be

\begin{align*}
t_k = k \Delta t \;\; \text{for} \;\; k = 0, 1, 2, \cdots
\end{align*} for some
small time step $\Delta t$.

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH257/December_2011/Math_Exam_Resources_Courses_MATH257_December_2011_Question_4_(a)_4a_2.png}

At $x = x_n$ and $t = t_k$, equation (1) becomes

\begin{align*}
u(x_n,t_{k+1}) = u(x_n,t_k) + \frac{\Delta t}{(\Delta x)^2}[u(x_{n+1}, t_k) - 2 u(x_n,t_k) + u(x_{n-1}, t_k)] + t_k \Delta t  .
\end{align*}
To get the above, we used

\begin{align*}
t+ \Delta t = t_{k+1} , x + \Delta x = x_{n+1} \;\; \text{and} \;\; x - \Delta x = x_{n-1}.
\end{align*}
Using the notation $u_n^k \approx u(x_n, t_k)$, we can write the above
as

\begin{align*}
u_n^{k+1} = u_n^k + \frac{\Delta t}{(\Delta x)^2}[u_{n+1}^k - 2 u_n^k + u_{n-1}^k] + t_k \Delta t .  \;\; (2)
\end{align*}

If we look at the above equation, we see that for each fixed $k$, it
gives us a scheme to compute $u_n^{k+1}$ once $u_n^k$ is known for
$n =0 ,1, 2, \cdots, N$.
