the initial condition $u(x,0) = 0$, we set

\begin{align*}
u_n^0 = 0 \;\; \text{for} \;\; n = 0,1,2,\cdots, N .
\end{align*} For the
boundary condition $u(1,t) = 0$, we set

\begin{align*}
u_N^k = 0 \;\; \text{for} \;\; k = 1,2,3, \cdots  .
\end{align*} Now, for the
boundary condition $u_x(0,t) = 0$, there is more than one way to handle
that. One possible way is to set

\begin{align*}
\frac{u(0,t) - u(0 - \Delta x,t)}{\Delta x} = 0
\end{align*} which implies

\begin{align*}
u(0,t) = u(-\Delta x, t) \,
\end{align*} If we allow an extra mesh point to the
left of $x_0$, the above gives

\begin{align*}
u_0^k = u_{-1}^k .
\end{align*} Hence, for $n =0$, equation (2) can be rewritten
as

\begin{align*}
u_0^{k+1} &= u_0^k + \frac{\Delta t}{(\Delta x)^2}[u_{1}^k - 2 u_0^k + u_{-1}^k] + t_k \Delta t  \\
&=  u_0^k + \frac{\Delta t}{(\Delta x)^2}[u_{1}^k - u_0^k] + t_k \Delta t . 
\end{align*}

